    id: "tick-store",
    title: "Design a low-latency time-series tick store",
    difficulty: "Hard",
    prompt: `Design a storage system for market tick data: every quote and trade for a large universe of instruments, captured continuously.\nWrites are relentless and append-only during market hours; reads are heavy analytical range scans by researchers (e.g. 'all trades for AAPL between 09:30 and 10:00 over the last year').\nDesign for both the write-heavy ingest path and the fast range-query read path.`,
    requirements: [
      "Functional: ingest millions of ticks/sec, append-only, ordered by time per symbol.",
      "Functional: fast range queries by (symbol, time-range) and column projection.",
      "Functional: as-of / point-in-time joins for aligning multiple series.",
      "Non-functional: high write throughput with bounded ingest latency; durable.",
      "Non-functional: compact on disk (years of data) and fast cold-scan throughput.",
      "Non-functional: read scans shouldn't be starved by concurrent writes.",
      "Edge cases: late/out-of-order ticks, schema evolution, downsampling/retention.",
    ],
    talkingPoints: `CLARIFY SCOPE\n- Granularity & retention: full tick (every quote update) vs trades-only vs 1-minute bars? Full quote data is orders of magnitude larger. Often: keep recent full tick hot, downsample older to bars in cold tiers.\n- Read pattern: mostly recent intraday (low latency) or long historical scans (throughput)? This shapes the tiering.\n\nWHY COLUMNAR\n- Tick data is wide but queries touch few columns (e.g. just price+size). Columnar layout (Parquet/Arrow, or a native kdb+/ArcticDB style) stores each field contiguously: read only the columns you need, and homogeneous columns compress brilliantly. Row stores waste IO reading fields you discard.\n- Compression: delta-encode timestamps (monotonic -> tiny deltas), delta-of-delta + zigzag for the clustered values, dictionary-encode symbols, then a fast codec (LZ4/Zstd). Gorilla-style XOR encoding for floats. This is the difference between TBs and PBs.\n\nPARTITIONING / LAYOUT\n- Partition by date, then by symbol (or symbol-bucket). A query for (AAPL, 09:30-10:00, last year) prunes to ~252 small partitions and reads only the trades column. Sort within partition by time so range scans are sequential IO.\n- Keep per-partition min/max time + zone maps so the planner skips partitions without scanning them.\n\nWRITE PATH (LSM-style)\n- Append-only ingest: writes land in an in-memory write buffer (per symbol, time-ordered) backed by a WAL for durability. Periodically flush sorted immutable segments to disk (LSM tree). This turns random-looking per-symbol writes into large sequential disk writes — the only way to hit millions/sec.\n- Background compaction merges small segments into larger sorted/columnar files and applies downsampling/retention. Compaction competes with reads for IO — schedule it off-peak (after close) and rate-limit it.\n- Late/out-of-order ticks: the in-memory buffer can absorb modest reordering before flush; for very late data, write to the correct time partition and let compaction merge. Tag with an ingest timestamp for bitemporal correctness.\n\nREAD PATH\n- Memory-map hot segments; use partition pruning + zone maps to skip data; vectorized columnar scan (SIMD) over the projected columns. Cache hot recent partitions in RAM.\n- As-of joins: to align two series at each tick of one, do a merge-join on sorted timestamps taking the most-recent value of the other (classic asof join — kdb+/pandas merge_asof). Sorted-by-time layout makes this linear.\n\nSEPARATING READ/WRITE CONTENDED IO\n- Append-only + immutable segments mean readers never block writers (MVCC-ish: readers see a consistent set of sealed segments). Put the WAL on fast NVMe; tier cold partitions to cheaper object storage (S3) with the hot index in RAM.\n\nTRADEOFFS\n- LSM gives huge write throughput at the cost of read amplification (a query may touch several segments until compaction merges them) and compaction CPU/IO. A B-tree/in-place store gives clean reads but chokes on this write rate. For append-only time-series, LSM + columnar is the standard answer.\n- Schema evolution: columnar formats add columns cheaply; version the schema per segment.`,
    quantAngle: `The tick store is the research firm's memory — a Millennium interviewer wants columnar + LSM + partition-pruning reasoning, because researchers' backtests live or die on whether a multi-year, multi-symbol range scan returns in seconds instead of minutes.`,
